A [bivariate Gaussian probability density function](/Bivariate_Gaussian_distribution) centered at (0, 0), with covariance matrix given by

$$
{\begin{bmatrix}1&0.5\\0.5&1\end{bmatrix}}
$$

Sample points from a [bivariate Gaussian distribution](/Bivariate_Gaussian_distribution) with a standard deviation of 3 in roughly the lower left–upper right direction and of 1 in the orthogonal direction. Because the x and y components co-vary, the variances of $x$ and $y$ do not fully describe the distribution. A $2\times 2$ covariance matrix is needed; the directions of the arrows correspond to the [eigenvectors](/Eigenvector) of this covariance matrix and their lengths to the square roots of the [eigenvalues](/Eigenvalues).

